>> ShellSession({'command': 'cat > /app/solve3.py << \'PYEOF\'\nimport numpy as np\nfrom scipy.optimize import brentq\n\nn = 150000\nlog_n = np.log(n)\ntarget_kl = 10.0\n\n# The 2-group approach gives very large backward KL.\n# The problem is that with 2 groups, when we make the high group\n# concentrated enough for forward KL=10, the low group becomes\n# extremely small, making backward KL huge.\n\n# We need a 3-group approach:\n# Group 1: k1 elements with prob p1 (high)\n# Group 2: k2 elements with prob p2 (medium)\n# Group 3: (n-k1-k2) elements with prob p3 (low, but not too low)\n\n# This gives us more flexibility. Let\'s try:\n# k1 elements at p1, (n-k1) elements at p3\n# where p3 is not too small.\n\n# Actually, let me think about this differently.\n# \n# KL(P||U) = log(n) - H(P) = 10 => H(P) = log(n) - 10 ≈ 1.9184\n# KL(U||P) = -log(n) - mean(log(P)) = 10 => mean(log(P)) = -log(n) - 10 ≈ -21.9184\n#\n# So we need:\n# - Entropy H(P) ≈ 1.9184 (quite low, very concentrated)\n# - Mean of log(P) ≈ -21.9184\n#\n# For a distribution with k elements at prob p and (n-k) at prob q:\n# H(P) = -k*p*log(p) - (n-k)*q*log(q)\n# mean(log(P)) = (k/n)*log(p) + ((n-k)/n)*log(q)\n#\n# With 2 groups and 2 constraints, we can solve for p and q given k.\n# But we saw that for k=1, backward KL is too large.\n#\n# The issue: when k=1 and p is large, q = (1-p)/(n-1) is tiny,\n# making log(q) very negative, which makes mean(log(P)) very negative,\n# which makes KL(U||P) very large.\n#\n# To reduce KL(U||P), we need q to be larger (less negative log(q)).\n# This means p should be smaller, but then KL(P||U) decreases too.\n#\n# With k=1, we have 1 degree of freedom, so we can only satisfy 1 constraint.\n# We need k>1 to have more degrees of freedom.\n#\n# But with k>1 and 2 groups, we still have 1 degree of freedom (p determines q).\n# So we can only satisfy 1 constraint with 2 groups regardless of k.\n#\n# We need at least 3 groups to have 2 degrees of freedom.\n\n# 3-group approach:\n#